As a professional mediator, I often find that what clients are really looking for is some real certainty that they can be heard, that there is some point where this process is over. That can be quite an overwhelming thought, to not know how to reach out and get started when they are so skeptical. Thus, it usually takes an initial consultation under the most dire of situations and a referral. But it generally does not work out that way.

Clients of the Children Experivce often hear about mediating their separation first hand from the mediators. Using this information as a jumping off point (recall, folks tend to involve professionals they know, like and trust), filing of the proper documents and detailing the costs is a successful referral strategy. Plus, the fact that it has a lower cost face-to-face alternative is huge!

Now, not every child custody scenario will benefit from mediation, and that is clarified along the way, but in general, when mom and dad say the "D" word the first place the kid knows about it is mediation - which honestly, for kids, is a consideration. But for society at large, it is beneficial, too. Most therapists recognize the feasibility of therapy when learning how to separate better.
